content.text: HTML Semantic Elements
Semantic elements = elements with a meaning.
content.html: Semantic elements = elements with a meaning.

content.text: What are Semantic Elements?
A semantic element clearly describes its meaning to both the browser and the developer.
content.html: A semantic element clearly describes its meaning to both the browser and the developer.

content.text: Examples of non-semantic elements: <div> and <span> - Tells nothing about its content.
content.html: Examples of non-semantic elements: <div> and <span> - Tells nothing about its content.

content.text:
Examples of semantic elements: , , and
- Clearly defines its content.
content.html: Examples of semantic elements: <img>, <table>, and <article> - Clearly defines its content.

content.text: Semantic Elements in HTML
Many web sites contain HTML code like: <div id="nav"> <div class="header"> <div id="footer"> to indicate navigation, header, and footer.
content.html: Many web sites contain HTML code like: <div id="nav"> <div class="header"> <div id="footer"> to indicate navigation, header, and footer.

content.text: HTML <section> Element
The <section> element defines a section in a document.
content.html: The <section> element defines a section in a document.

content.text: According to W3C's HTML documentation: "A section is a thematic grouping of content, typically with a heading."
content.html: According to W3C's HTML documentation: "A section is a thematic grouping of content, typically with a heading."

content.text: Examples of where a <section> element can be used:
content.html: Examples of where a <section> element can be used:

content.text: A web page could normally be split into sections for introduction, content, and contact information.
content.html: A web page could normally be split into sections for introduction, content, and contact information.

content.code:
WWF

The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) is an international organization working on issues regarding the conservation, research and restoration of the environment, formerly named the World Wildlife Fund. WWF was founded in 1961.

WWF's Panda symbol

The Panda has become the symbol of WWF. The well-known panda logo of WWF originated from a panda named Chi Chi that was transferred from the Beijing Zoo to the London Zoo in the same year of the establishment of WWF.
content.code_html:
<section>
<h1>WWF</h1>
<p>The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) is an international organization working on issues regarding the conservation, research and restoration of the environment, formerly named the World Wildlife Fund. WWF was founded in 1961.</p>
</section>

<section>
<h1>WWF's Panda symbol</h1>
<p>The Panda has become the symbol of WWF. The well-known panda logo of WWF originated from a panda named Chi Chi that was transferred from the Beijing Zoo to the London Zoo in the same year of the establishment of WWF.</p>
</section>

content.text: HTML <article> Element
The <article> element specifies independent, self-contained content.
content.html: The <article> element specifies independent, self-contained content.

content.text: An article should make sense on its own, and it should be possible to distribute it independently from the rest of the web site.

content.code:
Google Chrome

Google Chrome is a web browser developed by Google, released in 2008. Chrome is the world's most popular web browser today!

Mozilla Firefox

Mozilla Firefox is an open-source web browser developed by Mozilla. Firefox has been the second most popular web browser since January, 2018.

Microsoft Edge

Microsoft Edge is a web browser developed by Microsoft, released in 2015. Microsoft Edge replaced Internet Explorer.

content.code:
Most Popular Browsers

 
   

Google Chrome

   

Google Chrome is a web browser developed by Google, released in 2008. Chrome is the world's most popular web browser today!

 
 
   

Mozilla Firefox

   

Mozilla Firefox is an open-source web browser developed by Mozilla. Firefox has been the second most popular web browser since January, 2018.

 
 
   

Microsoft Edge

   

Microsoft Edge is a web browser developed by Microsoft, released in 2015. Microsoft Edge replaced Internet Explorer.
content.code_html:
<html>
<head>
<style>
.all-browsers {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 5px;
  background-color: lightgray;
}

.all-browsers > h1, .browser {
  margin: 10px;
  padding: 5px;
}

.browser {
  background: white;
}

.browser > h2, p {
  margin: 4px;
  font-size: 90%;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<article class="all-browsers">
  <h1>Most Popular Browsers</h1>
  <article class="browser">
    <h2>Google Chrome</h2>
    <p>Google Chrome is a web browser developed by Google, released in 2008. Chrome is the world's most popular web browser today!</p>
  </article>
  <article class="browser">
    <h2>Mozilla Firefox</h2>
    <p>Mozilla Firefox is an open-source web browser developed by Mozilla. Firefox has been the second most popular web browser since January, 2018.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="browser">
    <h2>Microsoft Edge</h2>
    <p>Microsoft Edge is a web browser developed by Microsoft, released in 2015. Microsoft Edge replaced Internet Explorer.</p>
  </article>
</article>

</body>
</html>

content.text: Nesting <article> in <section> or Vice Versa?
The <article> element specifies independent, self-contained content.
content.html: The <article> element specifies independent, self-contained content.

content.text: The <section> element defines section in a document.
content.html: The <section> element defines section in a document.

content.text: Can we use the definitions to decide how to nest those elements? No, we cannot!
content.html: Can we use the definitions to decide how to nest those elements? No, we cannot!

content.text: So, you will find HTML pages with <section> elements containing <article> elements, and <article> elements containing <section> elements.
content.html: So, you will find HTML pages with <section> elements containing <article> elements, and <article> elements containing <section> elements.

content.text: HTML <header> Element
The <header> element represents a container for introductory content or a set of navigational links.

content.text: Note: You can have several <header> elements in one HTML document. However, <header> cannot be placed within a <footer> , <address> or another <header> element.

content.code:

WWF's mission:

WWF's mission is to stop the degradation of our planet's natural environment,   and build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature.

content.text: HTML <nav> Element
The <nav> element defines a set of navigation links.
content.html: The <nav> element defines a set of navigation links.

content.text: Notice that NOT all links of a document should be inside a <nav> element. The <nav> element is intended only for major blocks of navigation links.
content.html: Notice that NOT all links of a document should be inside a <nav> element. The <nav> element is intended only for major blocks of navigation links.

content.text: Browsers, such as screen readers for disabled users, can use this element to determine whether to omit the initial rendering of this content.
content.html: Browsers, such as screen readers for disabled users, can use this element to determine whether to omit the initial rendering of this content.

content.code_html:
<nav>
  <a href="/html/">HTML</a> |
  <a href="/css/">CSS</a> |
  <a href="/js/">JavaScript</a> |
  <a href="/jquery/">jQuery</a>
</nav>

content.text: HTML <aside> Element
The <aside> element defines some content aside from the content it is placed in (like a sidebar).
content.html: The <aside> element defines some content aside from the content it is placed in (like a sidebar).

content.text: The <aside> content should be indirectly related to the surrounding content.
content.html: The <aside> content should be indirectly related to the surrounding content.

content.text: HTML <figure> and <figcaption> Elements
The <figure> tag specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.
content.html: The <figure> tag specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.

content.text: The <figcaption> tag defines a caption for a <figure> element. The <figcaption> element can be placed as the first or as the last child of a <figure> element.
content.html: The <figcaption> tag defines a caption for a <figure> element. The <figcaption> element can be placed as the first or as the last child of a <figure> element.

content.text: The element defines the actual image/illustration.
content.html: The <img> element defines the actual image/illustration.

content.code_html:
<figure>
  <img src="pic_trulli.jpg" alt="Trulli">
  <figcaption>Fig1. - Trulli, Puglia, Italy.</figcaption>
</figure>

content.text: Why Semantic Elements?
According to the W3C: "A semantic Web allows data to be shared and reused across applications, enterprises, and communities."
content.html: According to the W3C: "A semantic Web allows data to be shared and reused across applications, enterprises, and communities."

content.text: Semantic Elements in HTML
Below is a list of some of the semantic elements in HTML.
content.html: Below is a list of some of the semantic elements in HTML.

content.code_html:
Tag Description
<article> Defines independent, self-contained content
<aside> Defines content aside from the page content
<details> Defines additional details that the user can view or hide
<figcaption> Defines a caption for a <figure> element
<figure> Specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.
<footer> Defines a footer for a document or section
<header> Specifies a header for a document or section
<main> Specifies the main content of a document
<mark> Defines marked/highlighted text
<nav> Defines navigation links
<section> Defines a section in a document
<summary> Defines a visible heading for a <details> element
<time> Defines a date/time

content.text: For a complete list of all available HTML tags, visit our HTML Tag Reference .
content.html: For a complete list of all available HTML tags, visit our HTML Tag Reference.
